spans.text: OH Chatham , nursed in ancient Virtue's lore , To these sad strains incline a favouring ear
unpitying from the poor man's prayer
Far from the stormy waves of civil strife
her worth I asked no wealthy power
the uplands , if her mate was there , Or through the beechwood cast an anxious eye
The little history of their idle day
Where wont at night to blaze the cheerful fire , Pale Famine
her naked bones , Still sighs for food , still pines with vain desire
My faithful wife with ever-streaming eyes
with the morning's orient light I rose
vengeance to a guilty land , Sent Dearth and Famine to her labouring swains
to a guilty land , Sent Dearth and Famine to her labouring swains
joy to thee , and to thy children peace , The grateful hind shall drink from Plenty's horn
